{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_frannie_ver01/data/sn86072160/00514150369/1921012501/0180.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nCijc Casper t?ai!p Cribune\nIssued every evening except Sunday nt Casper, Natrona\nCounty. Wyo. Publication Offices: Tribuno Building\nBUSINESS TELEPHONE 15\nEntered at Casper, (Wyoming) Postoffice as second-class\nmatter. November 22, 1916.\nMEMBER THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nREPORTS FROM UNITED PRESS\n.1. E. HANWAY President and Editor\nW. H. HUNTLEYAssociate Editor\nR E. EVANS City Editor\nTHOMAS DAILY Advertising Manager\nAdvertising Representatives\nDavid J. Randall, 341 Fifth Ave., New York City\nPrudden. King Prudden. 1720-23 Steger Bldg., Chicago,\n111. Copies of the Daily Tribune are on silo in the New\nYork and Chicago offices and visitors aro wcloome.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nBy Carrier\nOne Year $9.00\nSix Months 4.50\nThree Months 2.25\nOne Month .75\nPer Copy .05\nBy Mail\nOne Year .....J7.80\nSix Months 3.90\nThree Months 1.95\nNo subscription by mail accepted for less period than\nthree months.\nAll subscriptions must bo paid in advance and the\nDaily Tribune will not insure delivery after subscrip\ntion becomes one month in arrears.\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulations (A. B. C.)\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to the\nuse for publication of all nows credited in this paper and\nalso the local news published herein.\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nOne of the most important utterances of recent\ndays on the business outlook comes from Mr. C.\nF. Weed of the First National Bank of Boston. It\nseems to us to be sufficiently important to pass on\nfor the benefit of the public, just as he spoke it to\na group of business men at a meeting called for\nthe purpose of discussing plainly the affairs that\nwere of the highest importance to the men as\nsembled. Here are Mr. Weed\u2019s own words for it:\n\u201cOne rainy night last week an automobile turn\ning too rapidly into Commonwealth avenue began\nto skid. When the wheels struck the curb it top\npled over. As the owner was emerging from its\nside a policeman came up and politely inquired,\n\"Have an accident?\" \u201cNo, thank you,\u201d said the\nowner. \"I have just had one.\"\n\u201cI suppose that there is hardly a business man\nin Massachusetts tonight who does not feel that\nhe has had an accident, and it takes a good deal\nof temerity on my part to stand up here and sug\ngest that the average business man really is more\ndazed than injured, that his machine is not badly\ndamaged, that the roads are drying rapidly, that\nthe danger of skidding is practically over, and\nthat if he were planning to go anywhere it is time\nthat he was getting under way.\nNevertheless, that is how I feel about the pres\nent business situation, and these are my reasons.\n\"There has been a great shrinkage in inventory\nvalues, but what of it? Deflation was bound to\ncome. We all knew it and we all freely predicted\nit. It has come, perhaps, a little more sharply\nthan any of us anticipated, but, after all, may that\nnot be a blessing in disguise? There could be no\nsound resumption of business until this inevitable\ndeflation had taken place. If it had been spun\nover a period of years a sound revival of industry\nwould have been postponed just that much longer.\nHas the bottom been reached? I do not know,\nbut I do believe that a basis has been reached on\nwhich trading can be done. Some things may go\nlower, but with many staples below the cost of\nproduction, and below the cost of reproduction,\nwith some as low as they have been in fifty years,\nit requires no prophet to say that a business re\nvival is just around the comer.\nNow, in what condition docs the average busi\nness man find himself to join in this revival. It is\ntrue that his statement of this January will be\nmuch leaner than his statement of last January,\nbut last January his statement was very fat. The\nreal test is, how does his condition now compare\nwith his condition in the years before the war.\nWith few exceptions, notwithstanding the heavy\ntaxes that have been paid, the generous donations\nthat 1.-ve been made to war charities, the heavy\nshrinkages that have been recently written off, the\naverage business man today has more capital than\nhe had in 1913-14. and, if he owns a manufactur\ning plant, that is almost certain to be in far better\nshvie than it was then.\n\u201cWhat the average business man needs today,\nand all that he really needs, is courage. If he will\nsit down and calmly analyze the situation this\ncourage he will cease brooding over his own\nlosses, and, what is more to the point, he will\ncease talking about his neighbor\u2019s losses. Os these\nlatter he knows nothing, but misery loves com\npany, and he is willing to believe anything and ev\n'erything and to pass it along. The result is that\nthe air is filled with baseless rumors and business\nhesitates. You have all heard some of these ru\nmors and you each know of at least one particu\nlarly absurd one by which you can judge the ab\nsurdity of others. But do not misunderstand me.\n1 am not saying that there will not be more fail\nures. There will be. Up to date the business mor\ntality has been relatively slight for so great a\nslump. But the failures that are coming have been\nmarked for a long time and discounted, and need\ncause no general uneasiness. The rank and file\nof New England business is far better off than it\nwas in 1914. Given courage it can go forward\nwith confidence into a long period of normal pros\nperity. There will be no more vast profits. There\nmust come an end to extravagance and waste.\nCompetition will be taken. The almost lost art of\nsalesmanship will have to be recovered. The!\nlevels of everything will be higher than pre-war!\nlevels, but they will be as stable, when found, as!\nwere the pre-war levels.\n\u201cI have spoken of the necessity of business'\nmen to cease rumor mongering.\n\"The public, likewise, should disabuse its mind\nof the erroneous idea that business men are all\nprofiteers. Think for a moment of the absurdity\nof the popular contention that retailers must mark\ndown their merchandise bought at high prices dur\ning the war. Why, bless your heart, these goods\nwere all sold long agd. Our big department\nstores average to turn'their stock over sue times a\nyear. That means, theoretically, that at the end\nof every sixty days their shelves have been com\npletely cleaned of everything on them sixty days\nprevious. Their buyers are in the market all the\nwhile picking up merchandise at the lowest price\nobtainable. This merchandise goes into stock not\nJo be held, but to be sold and competition keeps\nthe prices down to a reasonable profit.\nAnd, lastly, in this new era that is before us\nI think we should call it a healthy era. Business\nno longer is sick. It was during the bloated years\nthat are over that business was sick. In this\nhealty era the sanctity of a contract must be uni\nversally recognized. When a seller agrees to de\nliver goods upon certain terms he must deliver or\npay damages. And when a buyer buys he must\nlake and pay for the goods he buys. We have\nheard a lot about cancellations. That is altogether\ntoo respectable a term to apply. Why not call\nthem what they are. repudiations, and let the op\nprobrium fall where it belongs?\u201d\no\nA BIT OF PROOF\nWhen The Tribune said a few weeks ago that\nthe police force of the city could, with profit to the\ncommunity, clean up a few of the rough snots, j\nthere were those who doubted that conditions jus\ntfied any special action. Then the Chamber of!\nCommerce held an experence meeting and it was\ndeveloped that conditions were not only fully as\nbad as The Tribune represented, but a great deab\nworse.\nAll that was necessary in the matter was simply\nto wait for the proof to come. It was bound to\ncome, because the police department is largely a\ndepartment of bluff. Pretending to do the things\nrequired by law, and at the same time pulling that\nold worn-out stuff of attempting to deceive the\npublic with a bit of show and bluster.\nThe statement may be a broad one, but we be\nlieve it a true one\u2014the police department of Cas\nper has not in the past, and is not now, making'\nany sincere and intelligent attempt to enforce the\nstatutes and ordinances with respect to illicit traf\nfic in liquor, the offense of gambling and the prac\ntice of prostitution. What desultory efforts they\nare compelljid to put forth are purely superficial\nand makeshift.\nif proof were required, it is to be found in the\narrest of one, Devine, a police sergeant on the\nCasper police force, for operating a still and of\nfenses vagainst the prohibition laws.\nIt simply shows that the Casper police depart\nment is so grossly incompetent that its right hand\ndoes not know what its left hand is doing. That 1\nthe chief was not up to his job, that one of hi's\nsergeants could make and dispose of liquor un\nder his very eye.\nIf federal agents can come into town and dis\ncover crimes of this character and make arrests, i\nwhy cannot the city police department do the 1\nsame thing?\nThe police are supposed to arrest violators, and\nstop violation of any and every law, city, state and\nfederal. We believe that is their sworn duty. It\nis not the understanding that police officers choose\nor pick the particular kind of public offense they\ndesire to handle.\nThe Tribune has been entirely justified in call\ning attention to the laxity of the Casper police\nforce, the Chamber of Commerce is wholly vindi\ncated in demanding a cleaner city. The signs of\nthe times strongly indicate by the odor that there\nis something putrid in the state of Denmark.\nQ\nFrank Mondell and his supporters in the House\nhave already brought the Democratic payroll\nwithin hailing distance, and it is certain that there\nwill be a spring exodus from the town of Wash\nington; and, judging from results, Mr. Wilson is\nsomewhat responsible for the shortage of farm\nlabor for the past few years.\nQ\u2014\nSenator Sherman wants to know what Senator\nKendrick means by the El Paso statement to the\nNational Stockmen, that in case the Kendrick-\nKenyon law becomes effective that he will resign\nfrom the Senate and take a position on the Live\nstock Commission?\no\nFrance\u2019s notion is that Germany must pay up\non reparations and disarm. That is Premier\nBriand's idea also. He takes no stock in Ger\nmany\u2019s economic distress\u2019. The next thing the\nLeague learns will be defiance from Germany.\nWho is there to enforce compliance?\nThere was a mere matter of a hundred million\nof loot in the shipbuilding enterprise and the worst\nof it is that some very able and very distinguished\ncaptains of industry were involved.\nThe Bryan plan of reorganizing Democracy\ncontemplates the elimination of Tammany and\nwith bone dry prohibition as the paramount issue. I\nThe naval holiday is apparently winning sup\nport in the United Stales Senate.\nCbe Casper Dafip Cribune\nAmerican Legion News Notes\nState and National Topics of Interest to Ex-Service Men and\nthe American Legion, Which Designated the\nTribune as Its Official Newspaper\nDRIVE STARTED IN BEHALF\nOF AMERICAN HISTORY.\nDeclaring that the educational in*\netitutions of the United States are\nturning out graduates better versed\nin the history of Greece and Rome\nthan in that of their own country,\nHenry J. Ryan, chairman of the\nAmericanism commission of the\nAmerican Legion, has announced the\nstart of a legion movement to make\nthe study of American history and\ncivics compulsory in all public and\nprivate schools.\nThe legion\u2019s commission, according\nto Mr. Ryan, proposes to work out\nits educational program through the\nvarious state departments. Legisla\ntion, outlined by national headquar\nters, will be backed in the various\nstate legislatures by the legionnaires\nw ihe different states.\nMr. Ryan said that, while the\nstudy of American history and civicfl\nin more or less general, there are a\nnumber of schools in which the sub\njects are elective and from which a\nstudent may be graduated without\nknowledge of their essentials. It is to\ncorrect thia situation that the legion,\nIms acted.\nUNEMPLOYMENT PROBLEM\nAIDED BY THE LEGION.\nThe American Legion, which was\nquick to offer its aid to the police\nat the height of the crime wave, is\nnow establishing employment agen\ncies and aiding tx-servlce men during\nthe present low tide of industry. A\nnational survey of unemployment is\nlieing made by th< American legion\nWeekly and all posts have been en\ncouraged to establish employment\n'agencies by F. W. Galbraith, Jr., na\ntional commander.\nI luaHbOchusotts legionnaires have ob-\nItalced employment for 20 per cent of\n'applicants at their office. Employ*\n'ment officers of Minnesota posts are\n'discouraging to the cities and inter\nchanging Information In regard to\nprospects for employment in their\ncommunities. Spokane ex-service\n'men and their families who are out\nof work are being supplied with food\n'and other necessities by legion mem\nbers\nREHABILITATION IS\nPROMISED BY SOLONS.\nMore than 20 answers to the me\nmorial calling attention to the situa\ntion which surrounds the rehabilita\ntion or disabled veterans of the world\nwar, presented to the president, pres\nident-elect and congress by the Ameri\ncan Legion, have been received at\nnational headquarters by F. W. Gal-\nIbraith, Jr., national commander. In\n'almost every instance, the senators\nand representatives wrote that they\nwould support tho legion's program\nfor reform of the rehabilitation sys\ntem.\nParis. France, Post of the Ameri\ncan Jxigion has started a campaign\nto hold the 1922 legion convention in\nGay Paree.\nFOUR-FOLD PLAN IS\nSUPPORTED IN OREGON.\nThe state legislature of Oregon has\nsent a memorial to congress urging\nimmediate passage of the American\nLegion\u2019s four-fold adjusted compensa\ntion .bill. The action of the Oregon\nlegislators was unanimous. It Is be\nlieved to be the forerunner of numer\n\u2019ous similar moves on the part of\nstate legislatures in an effort to ob\ntain the passage of the bill.\nSICK AND WOUNDED\nBANDED INTO POST.\nIn recognition of the American\nLegion's efforts in behalf of dis\nabled veterans, the sick and wounded\ncx-soldiers of Detroit have organized\na legion post with a membership of\n'more titan 200.\nIMMIGRATION SYSTEM\nCONDEMNED BY POST.\nThe present system of immigration\nwas condemned by members of the\nBraxton County Post of the Ameri\ncan Legion at Sutton, Va., In a vote\nThe Wigwam\n1 SCOTTSBLUFF MILK AND CREAM\nThe purest and most wholesome on the\nmarket\nk\nMilk, per quart 1 7 cents\nb Cream, for coffee, per half pintl7 cents\nCream, whipping, per half pint 22 cents\nExcellent home-made\u2014\nPies Cakes Pastry\nRolls Bread Cookies\nE Corbett\u2019s Ice Cream, M. J. B. Coffee \u201cWhy\u201d\n\nThe Wigwam\nE. W. Elder, Mgr.\nMain Floor 0.-S. Bldg. Phone 187\nA BARGAIN\nCole B\u20144-PassengerB\u20144-Passenger Touring Car\nWire wheels, cord tires, bumper, looks like a new car, used\npart of last season, >2200.00 .cash or terms.\nPark Road Sales and Service Co.\nPhone 1223\nfollowing a discussion of the prob\nlem. Forty-nine per cent of the vote\nwas for stopping immigration entire\n\u00bbV; 11 Per cent for forbidding it for\ntwo or three years, and 40 per cent\nfor establishing an effective system\nof regulation. There were no votes\nin support of the prevailing system.\nLEGION MANUAL\nDISTRIBUTED.\nNational headquarters of the Ameri\ncan Legion has distributed 5,000\ncopies of a manual which members of\nthe legion's national speakers* bureau\nwill use during the approaching mem\nbership campaigns. The manual,\nwhich was prepared by the American\nLegion News Service, g|ve\u00ab a brief\nhistory of the organisation, outlines\nI the definite accomplishments for the\nbenefit of ex-service men nnd the\ncountry nnd sets forth the plans of\nthe legton for the future.\nFollowing an appeal by the New\nYork department to 8,000 ministers of\nall religious denominations of the\nstate, more than 500 cities and towns\nparticipated in \u201cAmerican Legion\nSunday,\" January 16. Posts attend\ned the service in a body.\nMinnesota legion posts will assist\nex-service men of their state to ob\ntain their quota of the 4,800 lost Lib\nerty bonds and 6,600 unclaimed dis\ncharge certificates filed away in\nWashington. D. C. Alphabetical lists\nof owners have been \u201cissued\" to each\npost by legion state headquarters.\nIdeas from ex-service men in regard\nto what type of war memorial should\n[be erected in the United States are\nsought by T. Semmes Walmsley,\nchairman of the national memorials\ncommittee of the American Legion.\n\u2019lnformation is also desired In regard\nto local memorials which have been\nconstructed. It should be addressed\nto 302 Marine Bank Building, New\nOrleans, I-a.\nMembers of a commercial club In\nWorland, Wyo., showed their appro*\nelation of, the American legion by ex\ntending free active membership to the\nmembers of Floyd Minch Post of their\ntown.\nF. W. Galbraith, Jr., national com\nmander of the American Legion, will\nvisit several Connecticut cities, Jan\nuary 31 and February 1. He will de\nliver a number of addresses in ex\nplanation of the situation in regard\nto rehabilitation of ex-service men.\nAccompanying the national command\ner on the tour, will be John F. Pick\nett, department commander; Thomas\nJ. Bannigan. state adjutant and Jus\ntus J. Fennell. Connecticut member of\nthe national executive committee.\nSCOUT MEETING CALLED OFF.\nThe Bny Scouts of TroAp 4' will inot\nhold any meetings this week at the\nMullin club rooms because of the sup\nper to be given there by the Indies of\nthe Altar society of St. Anthony\u2019s\nchurch. The Scouts are preparing for\na basketball gnms botwee-i Troop 4\nand the strong team of Troup 2 nnd\nthis game may be played this week if\nthe Scouts can obtain the high a \u2022hnol\nfloor some evening.\nGERMANY BACK IN FAVOR.\nTOklO (By Mull to United Press).\n\u2014That Germany is rapidly getting\nback into her old position as a favor\nite in Japan is illustrated by the\nfact that the leading book firms are\nnow gelling more books in that lan\nguage than in English and French,\nwhich took the lead during the war.\nOne firm alone has received about\n800 cases of German books during\nthe last six months, medical works\nbeing \"in the lead.\nI The\nI U. P. TRAIL I\nPeople\u2019s Forum\nLos Angeles, Cal., Jan. 17, 1321.\nTo The Casper Tribune\nI It has been'a month since we left\nCasper, and our minds are beginning\ni to think more and more of home, for\n1 home is home, no mattes how windy\nit is.\nWe went the northern route via\nBiUlngs, Spokane and Seattle. Thia\nis a wonderful trip to taker. We\nlived with the mountains all tbs way.\nIt was a great experience when we\nbegan to descend on the western tdojie\nof the great divide. Soon wo dropped\ndown from the region of snow nnd\nice and old winter, down into the\nv alley of sunshine, green grass and\nbudding flowers.\nWe spent a few days In Seattle,\nwhich is\u00aba wonderful city in many\nways. Then we took passjjee r.n the\nAdmiral Line for Los Angeles, stop\nping off a few days m tfat Fmn\nl\u00abco.\nThis, to our minds, is the moat\nbeautiful of all tho cities on the oyst.\nIt is a fine trip out Puget Sctind to\nthe ocean. But woe bet\u2018.do you when\nyou come to the ocenn proper. Near\nthis point the Columbia river bus Ils\noutlet, and for some rea-jon is a slunn\narea where nearly all the storms\noriginate, that sweep over the Rock\nies to the great valleys beyond. And\n\u2022ve had some storm! Bon>v said the\nwind blew\u2019 90 miles an hour. But no\neport of the atnrm interested us very\nmuch. Ke staid in our berth, wedg\n\u2018ng ourself with pillows to keep from\nbeing pitched out on tho floor. Mrs.\n(Tomer was about the only onn who\ndid not pay t-lbute to the briny in\nhabitants of the de?p. 1 think she\n;vas the only o.\u00bbt- not sick. For two\ndays and night* I iun auro the ship\nwont thru a grenter distarce altltud\ninally than horizontally. for when she\nwasn\u2019t standing on one end she stood\nci tho other, and lost little between\ntimes.\nThis is a country o' biggent things.\nWe have long known about tY.e big\ngest trees. But then- arc big in run\ntains, big valleys, big hotels, big\nchurches, big stores and big cases. We\nbecame wonderfully interested in the\nchurches. Dr. N. W. Matthews is\npastor of the big Presbyterian Chui eh\nin Beattie. He has over 7,000 mem\nbers. and a veritable army of helpers.\nDr. J. W- Brougher is pastor of Tem\nple Baptist Church in Los Angeles.\nThey worship in a theater. This is the\nchurch formerly served b/ \"Bob Bur\ndotte.\" Thu theater holds over 3,500,\nand people are turned away at almost\n.-very service for lack of room. Ono\nmust apply for odmisslo i tickets on\nSaturday to be sure of getting in.\nOne most refreshing \u2018hlng la that\nall thene preachers aio evangelical,\nbelieve that the Bib.e is the Word of\nGod. and preach It with almost super\nnatural i>owrt-, proving that tho old\nGospel has not only not lost its pow\ner. but that has attnictive power\nabove all the world can invent or do.\nThen almost the greatest of all is\nthe \"Church of the Open Door,\u201d Dr. R\nA. Lowey, Moody's old associate, is\nthe pastor. The auditorium holds at\nleast 4.000 people and is full at almost\nevery service.\nJust now the T:av. Dr. Court land\nMeyers, pastor of the greatest Bap\ntist Church In tho world, located in\nBoston, is holding a lavjvsl ctmpalgn\nir. this church, and Mrs. Cr>mei and\n1 are revelling ir. a truly great spir\nitual feast.\nCalifornia people seem to me to l\u00bbe\ngreat for churchcu. *i Is wonderful\nhow many people, both tourists and\nnome folks, go to c.'irch.\nBut I must mention the great cases\nend cafeterias. Tho Stater Case of\n'ton Francisco feeds over ten thou\nsand people dolly. At the largo cafe\nterias here there nro throe \"bread\nlines.\u201d as we call trein, vxtsndtng out\non tho sidewalk for hours, especially\nAnnouncement Extraordinaire\nPeterson\u2019s Famous Quartet of\n\u201cJazzeres Artistiques\u201d\nOriginally of Chicago, will play at the\nHENNING HOTEL\nFor Dinner and Dance every evening except\nSundays.\nThis arrangement will commence Wednes\ni day, January 26\nTable d\u2019hote Dinner, 6 to 8:36 p. m.\nI $1.25. per person\ni A la carte service as usual\nDancing\nFrom 9 to 12, SI.OO per couple\nMake table reservations in advance for dinner\nand dance.\nAs the proof of the pudding is in the eating, so\nis the proof of the playing in the hearing.\nCome and Enjoy the Evening\n2 Pianos-4 Player Pianos\nJust arrived from the Chae. E. Wells Music\ncompany. Denver. Exceptional values in both new\nand used instruments. Placed 'in your home at the\nDenver price. Any of these pianos! may be seen upon\nphoning 211 M for appointment, between 5 and 6\np. m.\nL. 1. GULRICH, Representative\nPermanently Located in Casper\nI In with us hi\u00bbd bought a cur and tiro\nlat the noon nnd evening ineal*\njoined in with Mr. an.l Airs. .Moore of\nThermopolis and bought a* car and\nare dellghtfu !y \"doing the whole\nPacific slope, Cvery day we go out\nto see the numberless of in\nterest\u2014enough to furnish a place to\ngo for every day in the year.\nThen there' are more rains on the\nWestern Coast than anywhere e!fc in\nthe United Stales, so far as we know.\nThe whole coiur. is .ined with the\nruins of the old Indian mlMiona.\nJust now there is a piny entitled\nTho Mission \u2019\u2019lay.\" gomg cn out i.t\nSan Gabriel, detailing in nust dra\nmatic manner the account vC the\nfounding, growth and decline of these\nmissions. It Is called the Oberam\naguu of America, and deserves the\nhigh title.\nIt may not bo generally known that\nAngeles is the home of nearly all\nthe scenario studios, in which the\nfilms for the \u201cmovies\" are made.\nNearly all their \"stars\u2019* are here, and\nabound in millionaire luxuries.\nThis fact emphasizes all tho more\nthe fact already mentioned, that this\nis a great \u2018.own. The\nchurches here have not lost their\nIsold on the masses, mainly, as we\nbelieve, because they preach the good\nCld Bible gospel.\nYou all know that this Is the home\nof tho orange, lemon, walnut, almond,\netc. Oh, what thousands of acres of\nthose wonderful fruits are found here.\nWe all had the pleasure of driving\nout to Miss Minnie Bucknum's won\nderful orchard. They turned us loose\namong the oranges, just being harv\nested, and told us to help ourselvoj.\nWhat anticipations we had. We nev\ner had all the oranges wc could eat.\nWe looked around for a time to find\nthe biggest and best, and began eat\nIng. And how many do you suppose\nwe ate? Tho writer was miserably\ndisappointed when he found he coul.l\neat only two!\nBut we must not write more. The\nweather has been fine. But today the\nrain is pouring down\u2014something\nmuch needed.\nTo all the friends at home we send\nregards.\nJ. W. CROMER.\nOBLIGATIONS OF MOOSE\nME ADMINISTERED TO\nHARDING BY CHAUFFEUR\nPresident-elect Warren G. Harding\nlately entered the Moose lodge and\npassed through the degrees of the\ninitiation ceremony of that lodge with\nhonors, bis entrance was made thru\nthe regularly prescribed initiation\nBEHIRWALOffI\nThousands Have Discovered\nDr. Edwards\u2019 Olive Tablets\nAre a Harmless Substitute\nDr. Edwards\u2019 Olive Tablets are the\nresult of Dr. Edwards\u2019 determination\nnot to treat liver and bowel complaints\nwith calomel. For 17 years he used\nthese tablets (a vegetable compound\nmixed with olive oil) in his private\npractice with great success.\nThey do all the good that calomel\ndoes but have no bad after effects. No\npains, no griping, no injury to the\ngums or danger from add foods\u2014yet\nthey stimulate the liver and bowels.\nTake Dr. Edwards\u2019 Olive Tablets\nwheiuyou feel \u201clogy\u201d and \u201cheavy\u2019.\u201d\nNote how they clear clouded brain and\nperk up the spirits, 15c and 30c a box.\nTUESDAY, JAN, 25, 1921\nforms andHn no way was the cere,\nmony adapted in order to relieve thu\nhonored member of tho realistic parts\nof the initiation.\nPresident-elect Harding, telling of\nhis initiation into the Loyal Order of\nMoose, said that when he was taken\nto the altar and brought into the\nlight and discovered that his chauf\nfeur was in the circle, to administer\nthe obligation of tho order to him.\nnnd when ho discovered that several\nof his printers in his newspaper plant\nwere in that circle, then ho\nfor the first time what it meant\nbp a Moose; and ho said that from\n\u2019that day to thia. \"I have had a bet\nter chauffeur than 1 ever had in my\nlife, and 1 have felt safer in my car\nthan I have eves felt in my lite, and\nin my printing shop I know that men\nare at work for my interest as wcU\nas their interest.\u201d Ho added: \u201cI\nhave in mind that the member who\npersuaded mo to join, said that I\nshould become a member of the Loyal\nider of Moose, not for what I could\nget out of it, but for what I could\ngive it. I joined on that theory, but\n1 find that I ain getting much more\nfrom the Mocse boys than I over Will\nbe able to return.\u201d\nNOTICE\nLadies of the Altar and Rosary so\nciety will give a chicken dinner at the\nMullen club, Wednesday, January 26,\nfrom 5:30 to 7:30, tickets $i..00.\n1-24-It\nWhen a young woman applied to a\nDetroit housewife for a position as\na domestic she specified that she must\nhave garage room for her automo\nbile.\ntflr\n1#\nYou Can\u2019t\nChoose Your\nCorset too\nCarefully\nIt can improve your\nappearance and if prop\nerly fitted will conceal\nfigure defects.\nCome and let us show\nyou a good Corset. W-Ef'\nCorsets we know will be\nevery thing the maker\nclaims for it.\nIt shapes not only a\ngood figure, but it does it\ncomfortably and it will\nwear as long as a Cor\nset should wear.\nThe Coyne\nSailer Co.\nThe Store of Quality\u2014\n\u2014One Price to AD\n138 E. 2nd St., I. O. O. F. Bldg.\nSTUDEBAKER\nAutomobiles\nI-\nJ SALES DEPARTMENT S\n11. E. Grude, Distributor J\nS 108 S. Center St. Phone 381 J\nSERVICE STATION\n113 8. Conwell St. Phone 1494 J\nGEBO\nCOAL x\nBaggage\nMoving Vans\nNaW\nPhonE343 &drUELXb\nJ. L. BIEDERMANN, Prop.","height":"19200","width":"16120"}}
